				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm{p}}=\int g(E)\cdot [1-{f}_{F}(E)]dE$$\end{document}where g(E)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$g(E)$$\end{document} is the density of states in terms of energy. Different from highly crystalized materials, the density of states for NiO are affected by the localized states40. In the end, larger and wider distribution of localized states resulted in higher hole carrier concentration in our case. We believe that the superior electrical properties of N2P-20M and N2P-20M-A originate from larger concentration of localized states due to more energetic sputtering conditions.Figure 5
